                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d563">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.00 Revolutions/281: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CWS1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-10-17T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 17, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>84. Your 218, October 16, 9 p.m., and 219, October 17, noon. Department feels
                    that the reply of the Minister of Foreign Affairs of October 15 to your letter
                    of that date regarding respect for international obligations is
                    satisfactory.</p>
                <p>As regards the other question raised in the Department’s 83, October 12, 6 p.m.,
                    namely, stability of the present regime, Department will await further report
                    from you as indicated in your 219, October 17, noon, before reaching definite
                    decision on question of recognition.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
